description: From Latin mōtō (“I set in motion”).

entries.meaning: (biology) Relating to the ability to move.

examples: Motor insurance is expensive for youngsters.

entries.meaning: (nautical) Propelled by an internal combustion engine (as opposed to a steam engine or turbine).
A machine or device that converts other energy forms into mechanical energy, or imparts motion.
(colloquial) A motor car, or automobile, even a goods vehicle.
(figuratively) A source of power for something; an inspiration; a driving force.
Any protein capable of converting chemical energy into mechanical work.
(Christianity, archaic, poetic) The controller or prime mover of the universe; God.
(prison slang) The fermenting mass of fruit that is the basis of pruno, or "prison wine".

verbs.description: motor (third-person singular simple present motors, present participle motoring, simple past and past participle motored)

entries.meaning: (dated) To make a journey by motor vehicle; to drive.
examples: On Saturday we motored down to Plymouth.

entries.meaning: (transitive, aviation) To rotate a jet engine or turboprop using the engine's starter, without introducing fuel into the engine.
examples: During startup, the engine should be motored for 20 to 30 seconds to allow the shafts to straighten out, as they may have become bowed under their own weight while the airplane was sitting on the ground.

entries.meaning: (informal, figurative) To progress at a brisk pace.
examples: Sales were slow at first, but now things are really motoring.
